'''Justin Richard "Richie" Edwards''' (born June 30, 1990) is an American-New Zealand former professional [[basketball]] player. After four seasons of college in the United States, Edwards returned to his adoptive home in New Zealand to play for the [[Canterbury Rams]]. He won the [[New Zealand NBL Rookie of the Year Award|NZNBL Rookie of the Year]] in [[2014 New Zealand NBL season|2014]] and later had stints in Australia and England.

==Early life==
Edwards was born in [[Albany, New York]] to parents Johnathan and Debbie Edwards. At a young age, he moved with his missionary parents to [[Christchurch]], New Zealand. There he attended the basketball-focused [[Middleton Grange School]], where he graduated from in 2007.<ref name=stuff>{{cite web | last=Egan | first=Brendon | url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/sport/9862527/Edwards-turns-from-towel-boy-into-real-Ram | title=Edwards turns from towel boy into real Ram | work=Stuff.co.nz | date=March 25, 2014 | accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> In 2008–09, Edwards attended [[Lakeland Senior High School (Florida)|Lakeland Senior High School]] in [[Lakeland, Florida]] for a prep season. He went on to earn first-team All-State honors with the Dreadnaughts. He was also honored as the county Player of the Year and the Lakeland Ledger Player of the Year after averaging 17.7 points and 9.5 rebounds per game.<ref name=bio>{{cite web | url=http://www.valpoathletics.com/mbasketball/roster/2011-12/5575/richie-edwards/ | title=#0 - Richie Edwards | work=ValpoAthletics.com | accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref>

==College career==
From 2009 to 2011, Edwards attended [[Hillsborough Community College]]. In his two seasons for the Hawks, he was a two-time All-Conference selection. As a freshman, he averaged 16 points and seven rebounds per game, and as a sophomore, he averaged 18.6 points and 6.8 rebounds per game.<ref name="bio" />

In 2011, Edwards transferred to [[Valparaiso Crusaders men's basketball|Valparaiso University]]. As a junior in 2011–12, he was a role player for the Crusaders, coming off the bench to record 12 double-figure scoring games. In 30 games, he averaged 9.4 points and 3.1 rebounds in 17.8 minutes per game.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thesundevils.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=2687 | title=#5 Richie Edwards | work=TheSunDevils.com | accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=stats>{{cite web | url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/richie-edwards-1.html | title=Richie Edwards Stats | work=Sports-Reference.com | accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref>

In 2012, Edwards transferred to [[Arizona State Sun Devils men's basketball|Arizona State University]] and subsequently sat out the 2012–13 season due to NCAA transfer rules. As a senior in [[2013–14 Arizona State Sun Devils men's basketball team|2013–14]], he played just 15 games for the Sun Devils, averaging 2.5 points in 6.7 minutes per game.<ref name="stats" />

==Professional career==
On March 24, 2014, Edwards signed with the [[Canterbury Rams]] for the [[2014 New Zealand NBL season]].<ref name="stuff" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Anderson |first=Niall |url=http://nzhoops.co.nz/edwards-returns-canterbury/ |title=Edwards Returns To Canterbury |work=NZhoops.co.nz |date=March 25, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502140417/http://nzhoops.co.nz/edwards-returns-canterbury/ |archivedate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> In 17 games, he averaged 17.8 points, 5.5 rebounds and 1.3 assists per game.<ref name=nzstats>{{cite web | url=http://www.foxsportspulse.com/team_info.cgi?client=11-8336-151868-298804-20462746&sID=&action=PSTATS&pID=197980659 | title=Player statistics for Richie Edwards – NZNBL | work=FoxSportsPulse.com | accessdate=October 31, 2014}}</ref> He was subsequently named [[New Zealand NBL Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://basketball.org.nz/Competitions/NBL/News/2014-nbl-final-four |title=2014 NBL FINAL FOUR |work=basketball.org.nz |date=July 7, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131014516/http://basketball.org.nz/Competitions/NBL/News/2014-nbl-final-four |archivedate=January 31, 2016}}</ref>

On October 29, 2014, Edwards signed with the [[Adelaide 36ers]] of the [[National Basketball League (Australia)|Australian NBL]] as an injury-replacement for [[Mitch Creek]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adelaide36ers.com/article/id/l31pyhj6eb6h1gw26nyx0wjy1 |title=Richie Edwards To Fill Creek's Spot |work=Adelaide36ers.com |date=October 29, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030104858/http://www.adelaide36ers.com/article/id/l31pyhj6eb6h1gw26nyx0wjy1 |archivedate=October 30, 2014}}</ref> On November 21, 2014, he was released by the 36ers following Creek's return.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adelaide36ers.com/article/id/1nsqruegqf2ly1r7bu9bxjjyu6 |title=Creek Back To Take On Wildcats |work=Adelaide36ers.com |date=November 21, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129033453/http://www.adelaide36ers.com/article/id/1nsqruegqf2ly1r7bu9bxjjyu6 |archivedate=November 29, 2014}}</ref> In three games, he averaged 1.7 points per game.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.foxsportspulse.com/team_info.cgi?action=PSTATS&client=0-189-88237-327335-19755570&pID=198961156 | title=Player statistics for Richie Edwards – ANBL | work=FoxSportsPulse.com | accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref>

On February 8, 2015, Edwards re-signed with the Rams for the [[2015 New Zealand NBL season|2015 season]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.australiabasket.com/New-Zealand/basketball.asp?NewsID=393801 | title=Edwards is back at Canterbury | work=Australiabasket.com | date=February 8, 2015 | accessdate=February 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Egan | first=Brendon | url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/65934208/exnba-centre-mickell-gladness-signs-for-canterbury-rams | title=Ex-NBA centre Mickell Gladness signs for Canterbury Rams | work=Stuff.co.nz | date=February 9, 2015 | accessdate=February 9, 2015}}</ref> In 18 games, he averaged 17.7 points, 4.1 rebounds, 1.2 assists and 1.0 steals per game.<ref name="nzstats" />

In August 2015, Edwards joined the [[Wellington Saints]] for their Asian tour, playing in Taiwan at the [[2015 William Jones Cup|William Jones Cup]] and in the Philippines at the [[2015 MVP Cup|MVP Cup]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Hyslop | first=Liam | url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/71401295/wellington-saints-bring-in-the-heavy-artillery-for-asian-tour | title=Wellington Saints bring in the heavy artillery for Asian tour | work=Stuff.co.nz | date=August 24, 2015 | accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Hyslop | first=Liam | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/basketball/71586557/null | title=Wellington Saints up and down at the William Jones Cup | work=Stuff.co.nz | date=August 31, 2015 | accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref>

On October 10, 2015, Edwards signed with the [[Plymouth Raiders]] of the [[British Basketball League]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://plymouthraiders.com/news/raiders-sign-richie-edwards/ | title=Raiders Sign Richie Edwards | work=PlymouthRaiders.com | date=October 10, 2015 | accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Ball | first=Jak | url=http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/bennie-lewis-departs-plymouth-raiders-new-signing/story-27958196-detail/story.html | title=Bennie Lewis departs Plymouth Raiders as new signing is announced | work=PlymouthHerald.co.uk | date=October 10, 2015 | accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref> However, he was released on November 7 after just two games, with the club citing "flagrant disregard for club rules, and for serious off court issues".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.plymouthraiders.com/news/anthony-and-edwards-released-by-raiders-for-serious-off-court-issues/ | title=ANTHONY AND EDWARDS RELEASED BY RAIDERS FOR SERIOUS OFF COURT ISSUES | work=PlymouthRaiders.com | date=November 7, 2015 | accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref>

==National team career==
Edwards became one of the youngest [[New Zealand national basketball team|Junior Tall Blacks]] when he debuted at just 14 years old in 2005. At the [[2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship]], he averaged 14.9 points and 7.0 rebounds per game. At the 2011 World University Games, he led New Zealand in scoring and finished third among all tournament players, averaging 20.1 points per game.<ref name="bio" />

